The triumph of the populist right in Austria, together they form 29%
Early elections to the Austrian parliament have brought according to the first approximate results, an appreciable weakening of both parties of the current grand coalition and an expressive strengthening of the populist right-wing party.
Heavy and special losses have suffered the Austrian People's Party (OVP), where the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously reeling.
By contrast, the leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZO), the head of the government of the state of Carinthia, Jörg Haider, prepares his triumphant return to national politics.
According to the approximate results, social democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of votes, so it loses 5.5 percent of a vote compared to the last elections in 2006.
The OVP has yet to end that loses 25.6 percent, nearly nine percent of the vote.
They are the worst results, literally catastrophic, in the history of these two great Austrian parties since the post-war period and especially for the popular who called this early election.
Still in early July, when the OVP left the coalition, the popular had in terms of preference to the SPO, a considerable advantage.
It is clear, however, that voters punished them for letting the government shipwreck.
Already in the first reactions to the results, speculation was heard about the resignation of the party president and, until today, vice chancellor, Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could be reached on Monday at the exceptional meeting of the presidency of the party.
Such an evolution would evidently facilitate the path of the constant and closest starting point of the electoral results, that is, of the renewal of the grand coalition between SPO and OVP.
Since the reinforcement of both parties of the populist right - the liberals (FPO) have won approximately 18 percent and the BZO, eleven percent of the vote - and that the Social Democrats at the same time expressed their fears that the same thing would be repeated in 1999 when the popular negotiated with the populists (then FPO was a unit, but in 2005 it was dismembered by BZO) for a government
For this evolution, Haider clearly bets who already announced that he is prepared to collaborate with any party and that he already assumes his return to Vienna, to national politics.
The Green Party has also managed to reach parliament although it has lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
No other party clearly exceeded the four percent limit and therefore is not part of parliament.
