The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not going to be long in coming.
That Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobile.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunication Office (ČTÚ) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming rates, a paradoxical situation is probably reached - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they are sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to lament that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, has also said that there is no longer room in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find any frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant decrease in prices against which classic operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the British market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, you don’t need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we inform you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking is the Penta group that, apart from this, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, it is enough for them to have far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large expenses in construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators are usually profiled with low expenses - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however, is often countered by the offer of tighter services.
Thus, for example, Mobile Tesco in Great Britain offers SMS at least half the economy with respect to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to a nothing trivial target group.
This operator specifically targets man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking — he’s the operator he likes and who can be trusted,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works this virtual carrier.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept like Poland could be hooked on our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický said: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of the service offer is relatively saturated"
There are no chances in the Czech Republic, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be any virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the R. Czech doesn't seem too hopeful.
Rather, it’s about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region,” Jana Studničková, a spokesman for the financial group Penta, said in a telephone conversation for mobile.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real Telefónica O2 competition in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, in order to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephone services but also mobile phone services.
And how much earlier, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly encountered all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to advance the meetings," said the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then, maybe they'll flash better times.
It seems that, by unofficial information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"Right now we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
To date, no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," said Vlastimil Sršeň, a spokesman for Telefónica O2 for mobile.cz.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2’s opinion, adds: “Until today we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop.”
He adds: “On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this time we should already have on the table some concrete contract that could be studied in such a short horizon"
Vodafone directs your attention rather to the fulfillment of the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of spending and infrastructure sharing.
We consider it as the greatest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s primary strategy in this field is found in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on mobile.”
Responsible offices - with operators nail and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a drop in prices and thus a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier to enter the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on ČTÚ was at the time of U:fon’s entry by the T-Mobile company.
It is attested by public information accessible on the ČTÚ websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: “In addition, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened to a fourth operator.
Regarding the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean for him and, above all, for his services great requirements.
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in trade tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (US).
However, it expressed its typical position on this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was closed.
To date, no agreement has been closed since the offer of potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for classic operators," Kristián Chalupa, from the ÚOHS foreign relations department, added to our question.
These statements are not surprising to the operator representatives.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, apart from this they must observe that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the fall in prices of mobile phone services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the fall in prices do not fall within the interest of the UOHS.
The dramatically shocking thing in this whole case really lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in the gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and has therefore no reason to intervene.
Neither operator has a dominant position therefore have no corresponding increase in responsibility in their market actions.
The tools needed to open up the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunication regulators," Chalupa added.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
Obviously there is a relevant market analysis drawn up by ČTÚ according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of the commercial tender a single market.
In this type of market naturally none of the Czech traders has a dominant position.
However some of the legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument were not accepted, at least for ÚOHS it should represent a warning that three mobile operators ascend strikingly in a similar way.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they clash with many similar impediments.
Carrying responsibility in ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the ÚOHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We have met him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was recently tabled for the extension of ČTÚ competition in the field of commercial tenders that was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This must be perfectly known by the representatives of ÚOHS, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
Everything's fine, when no one looks
At the same time, something like a pseudovirtual operator is still working unnoticed that in Czech mobile telephone networks there are already a few.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services which, however, only a part are public.
Usually these are companies that are dedicated to multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a few chosen get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the same instructing a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases were discovered such as those cited, it could be said of infringement in the conditions of contract that could result in the end of the collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová replied to the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies cited, it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make a not negligible profit and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows speculation of this type, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percent of customers.
These must also accept that the SIM card on your phone is not in your name so they cannot have it absolutely as a normal customer of the operators."
This is precisely what should seem to the minimally strange ČTÚ.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile operators turn their eyes on this type of procedure, why do they block the virtual operator’s input?
It is necessary to add that the ÚOHS has enough competition to discover this type of activities and if it will not want to be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When we will stop being the most expensive
As was already clear from the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant decrease in service prices.
At the same time, in virtually every country where the virtual operator emerged, classic operators more or less tried to protect themselves from this break-in.
The arguments used by these were practically all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have intervened at the moment and in none of the cases defended the operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to raise the first virtual operator and with it began to emerge others.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Organ all this case happens as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of the attributions in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually arrives on these lands, then the Czech mobile market will likely start moving again.
If any of the operators let in any virtual mobile operator it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to all four presentations of the new version of the Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the day of the official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the National Theatre orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are available four versions - two versions that are Solos, one male voice and one in female voice, another with Choir and another instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are in charge of the singing.
The authors of the anthem arrangements are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlavek regards this Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
Czech Radio has already said before that it intentionally chose the Solo singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried with both of them and then, also, with the Choir to look at the diction so that the text would be well understood, so that it would be in line," he said.
The official Czech anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home first played in 1834 on the boards of the Theatre of States in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
She gained popularity and people made her her own.
The first stanza of the song after the rise of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
