The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for the prevention of accidents Nissan has been inspired, this time, in nature, in particular, in bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C that is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Managing Director of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C is presented as an expansion of Nissan’s Four-Areas Safety Shield.
This robot intends to reinforce the collision prevention capacity of the brand’s vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that looks a lot like the Nissan Safety Shield.
But the most important thing is the bee’s compound eyes, able to see with an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles that lie up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to said object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor which immediately results in collision prevention.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at right or greater angles to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted up or down, or diagonally; it can only be moved in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It does not require saving intuitive information or logic from previous maneuvers, so it can work continuously with only a couple of dozen KBs of memory.
This may surprise, but we’re not talking about gigs of memory, not even megas.”
This is the first step in developing new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology Nissan predicts that will be introduced to standard cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles along the way.
