Talking asleep
Some kids talk at night.
I do not mean these who wake up very wise telling us something that has happened the day before, but children who speak while asleep.
The first time it happens maybe you get a scare, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disturbance called somniloquios.
It is quite frequent, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one of you have been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once in monthsS...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal bedwetting (pee sleeping) or sleepwalking, but it does not have to be so.
As we have already mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitation situations.
It is a little studied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or the opposite (screams, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him a way out in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disturbance that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to turn the child on too much before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or television series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children and they have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain internal calm.
This will encourage the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
Once the somniloquias appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day you will not remember anything that has happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even if he's talking, he's sleeping and therefore he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed for several episodes, you should consult or find out what generates so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common), do not fall into the temptation to do an interrogation to get information out of it.
You will not get anything, because being asleep you are not conscious to organize your thought.
In addition you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, with which very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
That creates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s not bad, it’s an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
