The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating its 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, he regained the public’s confidence that had seriously been faltered by the blood scandal contaminated in the 1980’s and 1990’s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980’s.
Faced with this drama and the discontent of the public, the Government of Canada conducted a public poll in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which aimed to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and make recommendations so that such a disaster is not reproduced further.
While Judge Krever was slow to file their relationship, certain provinces then created a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee accomplished this mission.
As a result of the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
" In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and much work during the years that followed, we have regained the public’s confidence,” he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population was henceforth confident in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that "trust is extremely fragile."
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, Décary says.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by the blood.
So we rely on one of the main recommendations of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we institute measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by the blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied had meaning. "
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market: nucleite acid tests that allow to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nucleated acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time when the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements allowed to considerably lower the risk of contracting AIDS by a blood transfusion.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"That means 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
So since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission of a blood product comes.
I think that you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion today to regain health without worries, "says the head of the leadership of Héma-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, in the example of the western Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
You have to be constantly vigilant, "says Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for sufficient supply.
" Needs increase because the population is getting older.
Since more aggressive anti-carcinogen treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has consequences on the network of blood donors who regroup on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All people with good health, 18 years old and who correspond to the eligibility criteria can however donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
Hardships are very rare.
But we must renew the members of this network of donors as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since the current life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate her blood," Francisine Décary slangs.
With a budget of 297 million dollars annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, among which bone grafts, heart leaflets, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered biomedical waste is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
" We celebrated a few weeks ago, the placing on the bench of our thousandth blood sample of the umbilical cord and it is expected to take out more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year, "says Doctor Décary who describes this program of taking cord blood as very popular.
“Many moms are disappointed that they can’t enjoy this,” since Héma-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
