Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Sr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice President and Director of Canadian Miner Barrick Gold
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the largest gold company in the world attempted a six million euro defamation process against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a "transparent public debate."
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation persecutions, but the law.
Without surprise, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, the best way to hold a public debate would be to harm whoever dares to hold a position contrary to yours?
The result of the lawsuit is of little importance, the authors and the editor of the book Noir Canada must spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers held by the mine’s almost bottomless pockets.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to scaring whoever will dare to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold had truly wanted a public debate, it is in front of the public that he would have had to present his vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally made by changing ideas and not by clubing.
It was therefore enough for the mining company to open its books, its records and establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent search equipment that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and support letters for the authors of Noir Canada.
Possibly Mr. Garver could explain how you can ask for a "public" debate by despising his views?
According to the vice president, it seems that this word designates only highly paid lawyers and not for all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What he doesn’t understand – or what he doesn’t want to understand – Barrick Gold, is that the public holding the authors and editors of Noir Canada does it mostly because it rejects the mining company’s brutal way.
This public is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but based on civilized changes of arguments, and not within the framework of what many people perceive as a persecution-gagge (chasing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just placed a request regarding the authors of Noir Canada intiminating them not to use this word anymore).
In addition to Mr. Sr.'s surreal speech. Garver, the Barrick Gold process is a direct attack on freedom of college and truth-seeking, essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to make a debate about facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and argue about subjects who dislike the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of many persecutions, who can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a transparent public debate, he could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
The excessive persecution of Barrick Gold clearly shows that, contrary to what it intends, it does not feel like making a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, but also for public debate in Canada, and it is high time for governments to place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
