What did they produce at the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory ?
Very soon, on October 8, criminal proceedings will begin against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing frauds of significant damage, in a business way, continuously and in an organized manner in addition to other crimes, including the falsification of documents.
According to the Prosecutor's Office, they used the funds obtained in public tenders for their own purposes, often justifying the performance of the tasks with false invoices.
The public funds and that of the municipalities - in full some 65 million HUF - stopped in part in the treasury of the Fiatal Baloldal organization and partly in the pocket of private people.
The method, which was also released by the researchers, was to justify the collection of the funds obtained in the public tenders with false invoices behind which there was no real execution, the different associations never fulfilled their obligations assumed.
According to the indictment, most of the bills were false.
For this they obtained the checkouts in the market of the Józsevaros District and the circular seals were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question that in the name of which company the counterfeit invoice was to be made was decided among others on that tour of the Upper Region of the Balaton where János Zuschlag sent to István Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he should choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for a bill for their consumption and they served as a model to make the invoices they presented among others in the competitions of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, in the Ministry of Social and Labor Affairs, as well as in the City Council of the Capital.
These invoices were mostly signed by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who according to our information rather wrote the necessary reports to obtain the public subsidies.
During one of his "studio travel" Sides he chose a brewery.
According to two bills issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomic center provided the food for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However - according to the manager of the center - so many people do not fit at the same time in that place.
Similarly, the bill issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation – later called Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért – was full of formal and contextual errors.
Well, a hostel in the town of Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, however, the bill included one hundred and thirty people.
But the manufacturers of great fantasy invoices also exaggerated when they pointed to the Pigal Kft gastronomic center because in the holding of books of the same - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
