Psychology of the Overlapping: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
New York University neurologists and economists discovered the neurological - economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
The scientists attempted to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in an auction and meanwhile the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (fMRI).
In both games participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is a fundamental element to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-prize" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to scientists, the increase in gambling is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, economists from the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against a person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product in question, and its members gambled.
Another group besides that was promised that if they win, they would receive 15 dollars more prize.
Instead, the third group received exactly 15 dollars before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the members of the group even lost that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the neurologists’ hypothesis, members of the group playing “against failure” were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the “winning” group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any economic theory previously existing.
For those until now explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so that we now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor in New York University's faculty of economics.
Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
In the world, about five hundred million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses in dependence on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and with body moods (sperm, mood of the vagina, saliva).
It is advisable for travelers to protect themselves by vaccine against virus A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested through poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jauntice appears on the skin and white of the eyes, the excrement becomes clear, dark-colored urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Annually one million people die worldwide in cancer and cirrhosis of liver disease caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected receive drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and even cancer.
Most people are infected do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys the liver cells and many times the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore, premature recognition, systematic medical monitoring is very important.
This disease is much more prevalent in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those who carry tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory check-up as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has cure if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so that it can suppress the contagion and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its objective is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
