Does it hurt less to who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also relieved the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in what way it influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
Within the framework of this singular experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and to the same amount of atheists, meanwhile everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in the series of researches in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate next to academics.
The analysis occurred as follows; they attached a sparkling instrument to the patient’s left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their gaze on two paintings; to the Virgin Mary, the work of 17th-century Sassoferrato and the 15th-century Lady of the ermine of Leonardo da Vinci.
The researchers were hopeful that the Virgin Mary’s spectacle would cause a certain religious mood among the faithful, while choosing Leonardo’s oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while watching the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics claimed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "they calmed down and in their heart peace reigned."
Looking at the religious-theme picture they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists as well, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person they feel very positively for, like a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
The Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases really changes our personality," Wright added.
After these formidable results there is only one question: what effect would it have for the regulation of pain if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of his size?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On his tenth birthday Google can say: he can be found both in people’s pockets and in the sky above his head; he knows where they spent their vacation, which doctors they visit and what they care about.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who parallel the Orwelian vision do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to gather as much personal data as possible about its users, and this is necessary to meet the original goals of Google’s founders: “We gather in a system all the information in the world!”
According to the Google leader, the company even after ten years of work that stirred the World is still in the initial phase of the effort to be able to treat all the information.
To the question that what is going to happen in five years Schmidt answered like this: I would like Google to answer questions such as "What to do tomorrow?" or "What would be the job that would suit me best?" - however, the software will not be able to answer questions apparently so simple until there is enough information from users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their navigation on the Network, the searched keywords, IP addresses and the pages where they went when the search ended are precisely stored.
Thanks for example to Personalized Search that debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can re-enquire what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches - in this same logic the Recommendations will be based, on which the system will offer us products and services based on the preferences previously defined and stored.
What if they take advantage of my data against myself, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who are concerned seeing Google’s information monopoly.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what may be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, longing for freedom, or rebellion against power.
However, it is an already confirmed fact that they not only retain, but in justifiable cases also give third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most debated example of recent times was perhaps the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google handed the Brazilian government the information on its website, called Orkut, to identify the paedophiles.
Instead, netizens who care about people’s rights in May were relieved when the company along with the EFF, an organization for the defense of electronic rights, successfully demonstrated in court that it was right in its litigation with the FBI: according to the ruling, Google cannot be forced, through any of the points in the constitution to supply any type of information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time the federal government managed to get on the pretext of reinforcing the child protection law approved years ago, about fifty thousand Web addresses and about a thousand searched phrases, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of Web pages and keywords of the last two months.)
This is quite contradictory the opinion about Google: it is criticized by those who fear providing their personal data because they think that their privacy is harmed, their private life when they start using Google services, and they rebel against it as against multinational conservative image companies.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, Internet users and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "avant-garde corporation", not so to its rival, the Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as conqueror of the World, no matter how much they both fight for the same objective.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, or money for their applications, the code is open and the program package is free, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it can also be because the geeks see precisely the very problematic relationship between the rights of people and the Internet that occurred precisely by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, leaving intentional footprints behind us and taking advantage of available communication channels, and while the measures of these varies individually, the essence remains the same: to show ourselves.
A normal young man may have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and may even link them with other services, such as Twitter or last.fm that offers a list of their music customs, then they can be included in a tracking system such as the FriendFeed or the Blip.fm, he may also have a blog, in which the most recent photo galleries that are stored in the Flickr or the Picsa appear automatically.
We can know numerous cases from which it is clear that for example the bride, seeing the flow of photographs the following morning of the common friends, learns who spent the previous night her fraudulent boyfriend or can fire the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion in his blog about the management of the company: one thing is certain, the definition of private life was completely revalued.
A person’s “online” life is what he shows of himself – this is the definition behind the behavior of our day’s youth.
And the one who wants to hide something, or at least pretends to dodge Google’s monopoly, can do it (starting with the Scroogle that uses Google’s search system, but leaves no traces).
There are many people who do not want to register on the collective pages to avoid that they can find them, but you can replace Google’s online applications, from text writing software to image and news reading applications with alternative versions which do not connect with giant servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
Public opinion expects almost openly the day Google shows its true face.
The company with its current value of 156 billion dollars is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca-Cola (110 billion dollars), AdWords/AdSense advertising surfaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, while services that are increasingly introduced cause serious headaches not only for Microsoft, but also for numerous other software developers.
Critical observers will, however, find the alarming contradictions as well: for example, the senior management flatly rejected the protest of the employees after doubling the price of the company’s nursery, considered the unlimited number of food of the employees too expensive, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 the Google gave in to pressure from the Chinese government and the company according to the agreement leaked all information that violated the good morals and interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the internal regulations of the company says that they will not announce any new services in advance, but only when it was ready to work, what if it is certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will be able to stir to the World: while some believe that the project of scanning and archiving of Google books and magazines will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be cited by the Supreme Court of the United States, others fear its Health system, because in it we can create our own health system
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database will be able to provide a good raw material for science fiction writers, the Scroogled, a novel by Cory Doctorow’s popular, describes in Orwelian form that future, in which a man only from Google data can be described alarmingly well.
