Smart car mimics bumblebee flight
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not imitation of obstacle sensors existing in nature?
For example, the bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at Japan’s CEATEC, the bumblebees gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-imitating BR23C-type car robotic steering system, which was given the characteristics of the bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technology director of RP and development and research.
The composite eyes of bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees play an important role.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, the engineers used the laser length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor of the vehicle that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the steering by turning the wheels as necessary.
Unlike any system currently existing, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
“If it weren’t, the vehicle’s robot could not react quickly enough to dodge obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotary movement and acceleration also the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is higher, which means that they have a longer lifespan than the lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the processing capacity of the data, much less the storage.
This apparatus in every second should only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No gigabyte, or megabyte memories are needed.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately dodge the obstacles, which according to Nissan calculations, in ten years from now, can be incorporated into the models manufactured in series.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to their destination, dodging the obstacles in their path.
