Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008 domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month’s prices and 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices – the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 percent from July 2008 and declined 3.9 percent from the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent from the previous month and 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased by only a minimum measure, with 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors rose minimally, down 0.1 percent from July.
The largest increase in price magnitude occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), due in the first place to the increase of 4.6 percent per month of bags and belts and the increase of 2.5 percent of footwear.
The highest price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical materials production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 percent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - in a minimum measure - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
They did not change the prices of papermaking, publishers and printing presses.
In the rest of the sectors of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 percent was recorded in August, firstly as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from July 1st.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period – in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors – the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 percent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electric machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally prices increased by 10.2 percent.
Electricity prices, gas, heat and water supply exceeded prices the previous year with 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade the largest monthly increase in prices (0.7 percent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, in prices of the energy sector and the intermediary sectors there was no change from the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediary industry (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods producing branches, there was a decrease of 6.8 percent and in investment goods 1.4 percent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF rose 1.1 percent from the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a 3.9 percent decline.
The price of our national currency in a month fell by 1.7 percent compared to the euro and by 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 percent over the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
